    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nUsing `vim.lsp.util.open_floating_preview` in insert mode with the default `opts` argument emits the following error on entering a character:\n```\nError executing vim.schedule lua callback: /usr/local/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/lsp/util.lua:1347: scoped variable: Invalid window id: 1003\n stack traceback:\n         [C]: in function '__index'\n         /usr/local/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/lsp/util.lua:1347: in function </usr/local/share/nvim/runtime/lua/vim/lsp/util.lua:1339>\n```\nThe invalid window id is different each time. No such error is emitted on cursor move or on escaping to normal mode.\n\nIn reality I hit this when calling `vim.lsp.buf.signature_help`. I fixed the issue in my config by setting `opts = {close_events = {'CursorMoved', 'CursorMovedI'}}`. The default value uses those events and `InsertCharPre`, my guess is that inserting a character also moves the cursor, so two events are emitted, both try to close the floating preview, and one errors because it no longer exists. \n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nMinimal nvim config\n```lua\nfunction Open_floating_window ()\n  vim.lsp.util.open_floating_preview({\"line1\", \"line2\", \"line3\"}, 'markdown')\nend\n\nvim.keymap.set({ 'n', 'v', 'i' }, '<C-h>', Open_floating_window)\n```\nUse the keymap to open a floating window. In insert mode, enter a character with the floating window open, and you'll see the error message. \n\n### Expected behavior\n\nClose the window without an error.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.11.0-dev-1216+g9a681ad09e\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nI don't think this is applicable, since this is part of the lua api.\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nLinux Mint 21.3\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nalacritty 0.14.0-dev (7077a5f4)\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nBuild from repo",
